But this conclusion would apply to the witness himself, not to the man who calls him, nor to the evidence, if principles which have been accepted in the past are recognized now. It stands to the credit too of the man who calls the witness that he has given the money publicly. The fact that the transaction goes on in public clearly removes the suspicion of evil intent, as Menochius has ex- plained even in this case. When the intent with which the money is given is doubtful, then the laws which forbid giving apply.
